text.label: Text
text.value: Ernest Adami was a Slovenian screenwriter, film director and columnist, but also playwright for theatre and radio, a film worker.Ernest was one of eleven siblings. His brothers Emil and Viktor Adami were known Slovenian musicians. And so was his nephew Bojan Adami who amongst others provided musical scores for a few of his films. Through this story you will experience a first glance on life time events shaping his biography and work ...

text.label: Text
text.value: Ernest Adami was attending the Eight-class II. City Boy's Folk School (Osemrazredna II. mestna deka ljudska ola) in Ljubljana.He befriended Fran Lubej, Nande Vidmar, and Tone Selikar.At the outbreak of the First World War, teachers and classmates called them the four-feathered clover. They were nature lovers. After the older schoolchildren left for the army, they formed a singing and instrumental quartet, divided the leadership of the sections in the teachers' school (Selikar for literature, Adami for drama, Vidmar for painting, Lubej for gymnastics, and all together for music), and organised exhibitions, lectures, concerts, and gymnastic performances.

text.label: Text
text.value: During the preparations for the production of Funtek's drama The Match (Tekma), in which Adami played the lead role, he befriended Marija Repi, the daughter of Alojzij Repi, an academic sculptor and teacher at the sculpture department of the technical high school, whom he also married after the war.

text.label: Text
text.value: During World War I (1914-18), he served in the Gebirgschtzenregiment (Mountain Rifle Regiment No. 2), surviving the 9th, 10th and 11th Italian offensive.

title.label: Title
title.value: Ljudje v viharju (People in the Whirlwind)

text.label: Text
text.value: He described his journey and experiences in his youth book Ljudje v viharju (People in the Whirlwind), which won first prize in an anonymous competition held by the Mladinska matica.

text.label: Text
text.value:
From 9 August 1941 onwards, he led OF meetings in the Ajdovina area under the pseudonym Marko.
On 16 May 1944, he and some others were betrayed and arrested for conspiration and taken to the Dachau concentration camp.
After his arrest, he was imprisoned in the Dachau concentration camp.
After the war, he was secretary of the Kolodvor field office in Ljubljana until November 1947.

title.label: Title
title.value: Ernest Adami, list of awards for his films

text.label: Text
text.value:
Short film tehvanje presented old Slavic customs of boys on horseback to win the affection of girls.
Ernest Adami wrote and directed the short film tehvanje.
Bojan Adami composed the musis score for the film tehvanje.
The film tehvanje was awarded the Plaque of the Italian writer Pietro Canoni at the XIIth International Folklore Film Festival in Firenze. The TV documentary was awarded by TV Ljubljana.

text.label: Text
text.value: His second screenplay titled Raunbachs Abenteuer (1933) told the story of Lindberg and his aviation entanglements. He wrote it in german.He sent it to Berlin for the UFA (Universum Film AG) competition.He saw it again in the magazine ivljenje in svet as a novella signed by a French author.

text.label: Text
text.value: Ernest Adami dies on the 12th of May in 1977 in Ljubljana.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E1.description: He was born in Ljubljana, then part of the Austro-Hungarian empire.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E3.description: Ernest Adami was attending the Eight-class II. City Boy's Folk School (Osemrazredna II. mestna deka ljudska ola) in Ljubljana.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E6.description: During World War I (1914-18), he served in the Gebirgschtzenregiment (Mountain Rifle Regiment No. 2), surviving the 9th, 10th and 11th Italian offensive

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E8.description: After his return, he attended a special course at the teachers' college and graduated in 1919.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E9.description: He first taught at the (old) boys' school in Novo mesto

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E10.description: Ernest Adami married Marija Repi and became son-in-law to Alojzij Repi, an academic sculptor.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E11.description: His next postings were in kocjan near Turjak (with his wife Marija) and Tomielj pod Krimom

label.default: Working and directing theater plays in Zagorje

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E12.description: He worked in Zagorje as an education worker and theater director.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E13.description: In 1941, together with other teachers from Zagorje, he lost his job and took a temporary job as a "shihtenrajber" (probably a shift census taker) at the Duki company in Toplice near Zagorje

label.default: Writing in different publications and under different names

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E14.description: The school in Zagorje was mostly attended by the children of miners, and it was in this proletarian environment that Adami began to write for the newspaper Jutro under the pseudonym Netko. He also published under the pseudonyms AMI (the middle three letters of his surname), Razorev (the name of his mother's farm) and Arnest a.e. and a.a. At the same time, he wrote youth stories for Na rod (after the war for the magazines Pionir and Ciciban) and as a publicist he published in Slovenske narod, Uiteljski tovari, Mladina and ika, and after the war in Ljudska pravica, Tovari, Filmu ...).

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E15.description: At first these were short impressions from the Zagorje valley, which eventually developed into writing feuilletons with more serious aspirations (the editor of Zvonek, Pavle Karlin, was the first to publish a short story by Adami, Deek iz sirotinice (The Boy from the Orphanage).

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E16.description: When he found out that they were going to be evicted, he moved with his family to Ljubljana

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E21.description: On 16 May 1944, he and some others were betrayed and arrested for conspiration and taken to the Dachau concentration camp

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E22.description: After his arrest, he was imprisoned in the Dachau concentration camp

label.default: Worked at the Kolodvor field office

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E23.description: After the war, he was secretary of the Kolodvor field office in Ljubljana until November 1947

label.default: Worked at the Ministry of Trade and Supply

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E24.description: He took up the post of press officer at the Ministry of Trade and Supply

label.default: Worked at the Directorate of Cinematography in Ljubljana

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E25.description: Worked as a propagandist and publicist at the then Directorate of Cinematography in Ljubljana

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E31.description: Short film tehvanje presented old Slavic customs of boys on horseback to win the affection of girls.

label.default: Short film V dolini Soe (In the Soa Valley)

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E32.description: Short film V dolini Soe (In the Soa Valley) was filmed as a touristic film exploring the natural history of the valley Soa.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E40.description: He made a film about the Auschwitz concetration camp titled lovek postoj. In it he infused a part of his experience when he was held in Dachau.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E41.description: The film Pepel, ki ge was made about the concentration campm Mauthausen, inspired by his experience when he was held in Dachau.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E42.description: The feature film Dobro morje was made in 1958, based on a much revised script.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E17.description: Worked as a secretary at the Red Cross, in charge of confidential reports on the orders of the Red Cross secretary Drago Zupani.

label.default: Worked at Fuel Office of the Chamber of Commerce, Trade and Industry

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E18.description: In 1943, he was given a part time job at the Fuel Office of the Chamber of Commerce, Trade and Industry.

data-ernest-adamic-tagging-bio-E19.description: Wrote an unpublished diary titled 240 dni okupirane Ljubljane (240 days of Occupied Ljubljana)
